7
00:00:57,912 --> 00:00:59,162
Story of the Week.

8
00:00:59,162 --> 00:01:03,000
3x More Production Coding – Anthropic Raises the Bar

9
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:16,612
A model that's nearly twice as safe as its predecessor and simultaneously solves three times more real production bugs – that sounds like marketing, but it's the benchmark reality of Claude Opus 4.7 published by Anthropic .

10
00:01:16,612 --> 00:01:24,425
Anthropic unveiled Claude Opus 4.7 as its new flagship model on April 16, 2026 .

11
00:01:24,425 --> 00:01:42,800
The most remarkable number: on SWE-Bench Verified – the leading benchmark for real software engineering tasks – Opus 4.7 solves three times more production tasks than its predecessor Opus 4.6, according to Anthropic's own measurements; independent validations are still pending .

12
00:01:42,800 --> 00:01:48,387
On an internal 93-task coding benchmark, the improvement is 13% .

13
00:01:48,387 --> 00:01:52,937
Anyone using Claude Code daily will feel this directly in their workflow.

14
00:01:52,937 --> 00:02:05,250
There's also a massive safety upgrade: 98.5% on the Visual Acuity benchmark, compared to 54.5% for Opus 4.6 – measured on Anthropic's own benchmark .

15
00:02:05,250 --> 00:02:15,312
This isn't a marginal improvement; it's a leap that makes Opus 4.7 genuinely suitable for agentic and automated production environments for the first time.

16
00:02:15,312 --> 00:02:24,025
Also new is the  effort level – finer control between maximum reasoning depth and latency, well-suited for long agentic runs .

17
00:02:24,025 --> 00:02:30,837
Additionally, Task Budgets (Beta) for token spend control  and a dedicated  command for code reviews .

18
00:02:30,837 --> 00:02:42,762
Vision has also been enhanced: images up to 2,576 pixels (3.75 megapixels) are now processed – more than three times the previous resolution .

19
00:02:42,762 --> 00:02:47,787
"Prompts written for earlier models can sometimes now produce unexpected results."

20
00:02:47,787 --> 00:02:50,937
— Anthropic, in the official release blog post

21
00:02:50,937 --> 00:03:08,937
Open questions: The price remains unchanged at $5/M input and $25/M output tokens  – fair, but the direct comparison with Alibaba's Qwen3.6-35B (free, runs locally) shows how quickly the market is shifting beneath Anthropic.

22
00:03:08,937 --> 00:03:17,737
How long will the closed-source model remain the superior tool when an open-source model on a consumer laptop outperforms it for SVG generation?

23
00:03:17,737 --> 00:03:29,575
Bottom line: Anyone using Claude Code professionally should test Opus 4.7 – but recalibrate existing prompts, as the changed model personality can lead to unexpected outputs.

24
00:03:29,575 --> 00:03:30,912
More Top Stories.

25
00:03:30,912 --> 00:03:35,575
Cursor: $50B and the Question of Whether the Hype Holds.

26
00:03:35,575 --> 00:03:42,350
Cursor is negotiating a funding round of more than $2 billion at a valuation of $50 billion .

27
00:03:42,350 --> 00:03:49,587
For comparison: in November 2025, the company was still valued at $29.3B .

28
00:03:49,587 --> 00:04:02,300
The driver is real growth: with an ARR of $2B in February 2026 and positive gross margins in the enterprise segment for the first time, Cursor has shown that the business model works .

29
00:04:02,300 --> 00:04:11,387
By end of 2026, the company expects an ARR of over $6B (company projection) – a tripling in ten months .

30
00:04:11,387 --> 00:04:25,275
The $50B valuation is not yet confirmed, however: as long as negotiations are ongoing, the figure remains speculative – and historically such numbers are occasionally revised downward during the fundraising phase .

31
00:04:25,275 --> 00:04:31,850
Nvidia is reportedly among the new investors – a strategic signal that goes beyond mere capital .

32
00:04:31,850 --> 00:04:43,000
For AI developers, this means: the market for agentic coding tools is consolidating, and Cursor, Claude Code, and OpenAI Codex are now competing for enterprise budgets.

33
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:48,050
Anyone who hasn't yet evaluated which tool fits their workflow should do so now.

34
00:04:48,050 --> 00:04:52,950
Physical Intelligence π0.7: The Robot That Improvises.

35
00:04:53,875 --> 00:05:01,150
A robot operates an air fryer – even though only two episodes of this existed in the entire training dataset .

36
00:05:01,150 --> 00:05:12,437
That sounds trivial, but it's the core of π0.7, Physical Intelligence's new model: compositional generalization – combining learned skills for entirely new tasks.

37
00:05:12,437 --> 00:05:17,275
Physical Intelligence unveiled π0.7 on April 16 .

38
00:05:17,275 --> 00:05:26,300
The model can brew coffee, fold laundry, assemble boxes, and yes, operate an air fryer – without each skill being explicitly trained .

39
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:31,387
Sergey Levine, co-founder of Physical Intelligence, described his own reaction:.

40
00:05:31,387 --> 00:05:33,000
"I am rarely surprised.

41
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:36,987
But the last few months were the first time where I'm genuinely surprised."

42
00:05:36,987 --> 00:05:49,137
As with all robotics demos, the gap between controlled lab conditions and real-world deployment scenarios remains an open question – robust generalization in real environments still needs to be demonstrated.

43
00:05:49,137 --> 00:05:59,250
The company is simultaneously negotiating a new funding round that would lift its valuation from the current $5.6B to around $11B .

44
00:05:59,250 --> 00:06:10,250
For industry observers, π0.7 is a signal of where generalizable robotics is heading: away from the "one robot, one task" paradigm, toward adaptive systems.

45
00:06:10,250 --> 00:06:16,362
Stanford AI Index 2026: Faster Than PC, Costlier Than Expected.

46
00:06:16,362 --> 00:06:22,737
The figures in the Stanford AI Index 2026 are sobering and impressive in equal measure .

47
00:06:22,737 --> 00:06:36,200
AI has surpassed both the PC and the internet in adoption speed: over 50% of the world's population uses AI, 88% of organizations have adopted it, and 80% of university students too .

48
00:06:36,200 --> 00:06:45,475
Meanwhile, productivity data shows real progress: +14% in customer support, +26% in software development .

49
00:06:45,475 --> 00:06:47,100
But the cost is visible.

50
00:06:47,100 --> 00:06:52,175
AI data centers consume 29.6 gigawatts of electricity worldwide .

51
00:06:52,175 --> 00:06:58,800
GPT-4o alone requires as much drinking water annually as 1.2 million people .

52
00:06:58,800 --> 00:07:08,600
And the labor market is already responding: employment among software developers aged 22 to 25 has dropped 20% since 2022 .

53
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:14,975
A third of organizations expect targeted workforce reductions due to AI, according to the index .

54
00:07:14,975 --> 00:07:22,600
Anyone working in or dependent on the AI industry will find the most important data foundation of the year in this index.

55
