00:08:09,337 --> 00:08:10,462
Tool of the Week.

61
00:08:10,462 --> 00:08:20,737
Qwen3.6-35B-A3B (via LM Studio) – Open-source model that beats Anthropic's flagship on a consumer laptop.

62
00:08:20,737 --> 00:08:41,850
Simon Willison tested Alibaba's Qwen3.6-35B-A3B locally on a MacBook Pro M5 via LM Studio and reached a clear verdict: for SVG generation and creative tasks, the model outperforms Claude Opus 4.7 – and does so for free, offline, on consumer hardware .

63
00:08:41,850 --> 00:08:51,575
What makes the architecture special is its Mixture-of-Experts design: 35 billion total parameters, but only 3 billion active parameters per token .

64
00:08:51,575 --> 00:09:01,500
The quantized GGUF version (Q4_K_S from Unsloth) is 20.9 GB  – no problem for a MacBook Pro M5.

65
00:09:01,500 --> 00:09:09,462
"Qwen3.6-35B-A3B running on a laptop is a better bet than Opus 4.7!"

66
00:09:09,462 --> 00:09:12,612
— Simon Willison, after direct model comparison

67
00:09:12,612 --> 00:09:22,287
Important context: This assessment is based on a single local test for creative/visual tasks – no production validation, no enterprise support.

68
00:09:22,287 --> 00:09:30,000
For complex coding tasks, security requirements, or regulated environments, the comparison does not apply automatically.

69
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:37,012
Particularly relevant for teams looking to build local AI workflows without cloud costs or privacy concerns.

70
00:09:37,012 --> 00:09:44,900
Anyone using Opus 4.7 for creative or visual tasks should test Qwen3.6 as a free alternative.

71
00:09:44,900 --> 00:09:49,100
Qwen3.6-35B on Hugging Face

72
00:09:49,100 --> 00:09:50,250
Fail of the Week.

73
00:09:50,250 --> 00:09:53,675
"80% Acceptance Rate" – And Why That Number Lies

74
00:09:54,600 --> 00:09:59,687
Developers report accepting 80–90% of AI-generated code .

75
00:09:59,687 --> 00:10:01,787
Sounds like enormous time savings.

76
00:10:01,787 --> 00:10:09,562
But it isn't: after revisions, rewrites, and debugging, the real acceptance rate is only 10–30% .

77
00:10:09,562 --> 00:10:17,412
The phenomenon has a name: "tokenmaxxing" – stuffing context windows with as much code as possible in hopes of better outputs .

78
00:10:17,412 --> 00:10:25,837
The data is alarming: Faros AI measures a code churn rate of +861% under heavy AI usage .

79
00:10:25,837 --> 00:10:30,475
GitClear reports 9.4x the churn compared to non-AI users .

80
00:10:30,475 --> 00:10:37,900
Jellyfish has found: developers with large token budgets produce twice the output – but at ten times the token cost .

81
00:10:37,900 --> 00:10:45,262
Junior developers accept significantly more AI-generated code uncritically and consequently have to rework more .

82
00:10:45,262 --> 00:10:52,675
Root cause: The narrative of "AI takes over the job" tempts people to equate output volume with output quality.

83
00:10:52,675 --> 00:10:59,312
AI generates fast, but not always correctly – and the more code is produced, the more debt accumulates.

84
00:10:59,312 --> 00:11:06,412
What we learn: Don't measure AI productivity by accepted lines of code, but by churn rate and time-to-stable-commit.

85
00:11:06,412 --> 00:11:09,800
If both are rising, you're shipping worse software faster.

86
00:11:09,800 --> 00:11:10,937
Number of the Week.

87
00:11:10,937 --> 00:11:13,200
29.6 Gigawatts

88
00:11:13,200 --> 00:11:18,337
That's how much electricity AI data centers consume worldwide – as of today .

89
00:11:18,337 --> 00:11:26,775
That's equivalent to the capacity of roughly 30 mid-sized coal power plants, or the total electricity consumption of countries like the Netherlands.

90
00:11:26,775 --> 00:11:33,212
GPT-4o alone consumes as much drinking water as 1.2 million people per year .

91
00:11:33,212 --> 00:11:44,212
AI's energy hunger is no longer an abstract future scenario – it's measurable, grows with each model generation, and is becoming the central infrastructure challenge of the industry.

92
00:11:44,212 --> 00:11:50,500
Anyone talking about AI governance without mentioning energy is leaving out the most critical variable.

